The container threat model.

Before stacking up defences, be clear about what containers are and are not. A container is a process-isolation mechanism, not a hard security boundary. It keeps workloads from accidentally tripping over each other on a shared kernel, but it is not designed to safely host untrusted, hostile code on a multi-tenant kernel. That stronger job belongs to virtual machines, and to projects like kata containers and g-visor that give each workload more of a real boundary.

It helps to separate what container isolation protects against by default from what it does not. By default it stops a container from reading another container's files, because each has its own mount namespace, and from seeing another's processes, because each has its own process-I-D namespace. Control groups stop one container from hogging all the see-pee-you and memory. And the network namespace controls which ports a container can bind.

What it does not protect against by default is the scarier list. A container running as root that breaks out through a kernel vulnerability, of which there are several each year. A container run with the privileged flag, which can do essentially anything to the host. A container granted the sys-admin capability, which can mount host filesystems or escape. A container that mounts the docker socket, which is remote control of the daemon and therefore root on the host. And a malicious or compromised image, which is a supply-chain attack. So hardening really means adding layers of constraint until the surface area is small enough that a compromise inside the container is unlikely to compromise the host.
